[3]
Date: Thu 3 Apr 2008
Source: Federal Ministry of Health, Family and Youth, Press release
[machine translation, abbreviated and edited]
<http://www.bmgfj.gv.at/cms/site/presse_detail.html?channel=CH0616&doc=CMS1207230051580>


Measles in Salzburg
-------------------
Health Minister Kdolsky reacted with disbelief to reports today that a
"measles party" had taken place in Salzburg, whereby children had been
deliberately exposed to measles virus infection. "The deliberate exposure
of children to infection is reprehensible and extremely irresponsible.
Suspected cases [of such exposure], must be investigated by an appropriate
authority as part of the surveillance of the outbreak and if appropriate
prosecution considered. This is about the protection of the weakest in our
society -- children."

The conscious attempt to contract measles infection means that parents are
placing their offspring at risk of serious complications in addition to a
skin rash, which may only become apparent after the lapse of several years.

Measles is a disease transmitted by droplet infection. "The best protection
is a timely vaccination against measles, a 2-part vaccination," stressed
the health minister. In this context, all parents in the affected area
should ensure that their children are vaccinated, and it is recommended
that contacts with known measles cases should be avoided.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Once again an outbreak of measles is occurring among the unimmunised
component of a routinely vaccinated position -- this time perhaps centering
on a school with a particular educational ethos.

The interactive HealthMap of Austria can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=47.6,14.1,5>, showing the location of the
city of Salzburg in the west close to the German border. - Mod.CP]
